& [ResearchSourceSet] is the bounded theorem-corridor frame
  + [source_001] is Wei Zhang, The Birch-Swinnerton-Dyer conjecture and Heegner points: a survey
    = link: https://math.mit.edu/~wz2113/math/online/CDM2013%20final.pdf
    = use: states the Gross-Zagier and Kolyvagin rank result as the broadest rank-part theorem corridor for elliptic curves over Q
  + [source_002] is William Stein, Toward a Generalization of the Gross-Zagier Conjecture
    = link: https://wstein.org/misc/sagedays18_papers/stein-toward_a_generalization_of_the_gross-zagier_conjecture.pdf
    = use: frames rank at most one as known territory and rank at least two as the difficult frontier
  + [source_003] is Burns, Sakamoto, and Sano, On the theory of higher rank Euler, Kolyvagin and Stark systems, III: applications
    = link: https://arxiv.org/abs/1902.07002
    = use: higher-rank derivative maps and Selmer-module applications strengthen upper-control vocabulary but do not by themselves create all needed elliptic-curve source classes
  + [source_004] is Burns, Sakamoto, and Sano, On the theory of higher rank Euler, Kolyvagin and Stark systems, II
    = link: https://arxiv.org/abs/1805.08448
    = use: canonical higher Kolyvagin derivative homomorphism supports the control-side corridor under hypotheses
  + [source_005] is Darmon and Rotger, Diagonal cycles and Euler systems I
    = link: https://www.numdam.org/articles/10.24033/asens.2227/
    = use: diagonal-cycle and p-adic Gross-Zagier work shows a higher-cycle analogue of the source/measurement/control shape in special settings

